summary:
The Security Council:

Adopted Resolution 1307 (2000) on 13 July 2000, 

Recalling previous relevant resolutions, particularly 779 (1992), 981 (1995), 1147 (1998), 1183 (1998), 1222 (1999), 1252 (1999), and 1285 (2000), 

Having considered the Secretary-General's report on the UN Mission of Observers in Prevlaka (UNMOP) of 3 July 2000, 

Reaffirming Croatia's independence, sovereignty, and territorial integrity within internationally recognized borders, 

Noting the Joint Declaration signed at Geneva on 30 September 1992, 

The situation in the UNMOP area has remained stable; however, 

1. Authorizes UN military observers to continue monitoring demilitarization of the Prevlaka peninsula until 15 January 2001; 
2. Calls on parties to cease violations of the demilitarized regime and ensure safety and freedom of movement for UN observers; 
3. Notes with concern lack of progress on confidence-building measures; 
4. Urges parties to abide by commitments and implement the Agreement on Normalization of Relations; 
5. Requests parties to report bi-monthly on bilateral negotiations; 
6. Reiterates the call for a comprehensive demining programme.
1307 (2000)
7. Requests the United Nations military observers and the multinational stabilization force authorized by the Council in resolution 1088 (1996) of 12 December 1996 and extended by resolution 1305 (2000) of 21 June 2000 to cooperate fully with each other; 
8. Decides to remain seized of the matter.
